{{Shrine
|image=[[Image:坐摩神社.jpg|250px|]]
|name= Zama Shrine
|location=1-9 Hiranoya, Daitō City, Osaka Prefecture
|coordinates={{coord|34|42|27|N|135|38|8|E|region:JP}}
|enshrined_deity={{ill|Zama-no-Kami|de|Zama-no-Kami|ja|座摩神|zh|座摩神|lt=Asuha Ōkami and Hahiki Ōkami|lt_ja=阿須波大神<br/>波比岐大神|lt_de=Asuha Ōkami und Hahiki Ōkami|lt_zh=阿须波大神和波比岐大神}}
|shrine_rank=Village shrine
|established=Unknown
|main_shrine=
|annual_festival=Third Sunday of October
|}}
'''Zama Shrine''' (坐摩神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|de|Shintō-Schrein|ja|神社|zh|神社}} located in Hiranoya, {{ill|Daitō City|de|Daitō|ja|大東市|zh|大东市}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|de|Präfektur Osaka|ja|大阪府|zh|大阪府}}.

== History ==
The exact date and origin of its founding are unknown. According to shrine traditions, Zama Shrine (Zama Daijingū) was the {{ill|Sōja|de|Sōja|ja|総社|zh|总社}} of {{ill|Nishinari District|de|Nishinari-gun|ja|西成郡|zh|西成郡}}, {{ill|Settsu Province|de|Provinz Settsu|ja|摂津国|zh|摄津国}} in the 13th year of {{ill|Kyōhō|de|Kyōhō|ja|享保|zh|享保}} ([[1729]]). The area where the shrine stands was originally a large pond called {{ill|Fukono Pond|de|Fukono-Teich|ja|深野池|zh|深野池}}, which was reclaimed as "{{ill|Fukono Shinden|de|Fukono-Shinden|ja|深野新田|zh|深野新田}}" through renovations of the {{ill|Yamato River|de|Yamato-Fluss|ja|大和川|zh|大和川}} during the Edo period. Consequently, {{ill|Hiranoya Mataemon|de|Hiranoya Mataemon|ja|平野屋又右衛門|zh|平野屋又右卫门}}, an Osaka {{ill|wealthy merchant|de|wohlhabender Kaufmann|ja|豪商|zh|富商}}, who was granted reclamation rights by the {{ill|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|de|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|ja|真宗大谷派難波別院|zh|真宗大谷派难波别院}}, invited the spirit from {{ill|Zama Shrine|de|Zama-Schrein|ja|坐摩神社|zh|坐摩神社}} (currently in {{ill|Chūō-ku, Osaka|de|Chūō-ku (Osaka)|ja|中央区 (大阪市)|zh|中央区 (大阪市)}}) as a guardian deity, marking the origin of this shrine.

{{ill|Zama-no-Kami|de|Zama-no-Kami|ja|座摩神|zh|座摩神}} generally refers to five deities: Ikui, Sakui, Tsunagai, Hahiki, and Asuha. However, shrine records from the {{ill|Taishō period|de|Taishō-Zeit|ja|大正|zh|大正时代}} specifically mention Asuha Ōkami and Hahiki Ōkami as the two enshrined deities. Zama-no-Kami is revered as the protector of the {{ill|Imperial Palace|de|Kaiserpalast|ja|皇居|zh|皇居}} and worshipped for household protection, safe travel, and childbirth.

West of Zama Shrine once stood the {{ill|Hiranoya Meeting Hall|de|Hiranoya-Treffpunkt|ja|平野屋会所|zh|平野屋会所}}, which was demolished in 2008.<ref>[https://trystero.exblog.jp/7094448/ 大東市、平野屋新田会所が解体の危機 <!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>

