'''Zama Shrine''' (坐摩神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|de|Shintō-Schrein|ja|神社|zh|神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinto shrine|qq=}} located in Hiranoya, {{ill|Daitō City|de|Daitō|ja|大東市|zh|大东市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Daitō City|qq=}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|de|Präfektur Osaka|ja|大阪府|zh|大阪府|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Osaka Prefecture|qq=}}.

<br />
[[Zama Shrine (Daito City)|Sazama Shrine (Daito City)]] is a regional [[Sōja shrine|Sōja shrine]]. It enshrines many kami of the local region.

It contrasts with provincial Soja shrines which enshrine all the kami of a province<ref>https://archive.ph/wip/XtZfZ</ref>

It is related to [[Ikasuri Shrine]]

== History ==
The exact date and origin of its founding are unknown. According to shrine traditions, Zama Shrine (Zama Daijingū) was the {{ill|Sōja|de|Sōja|ja|総社|zh|总社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sōja|qq=}} of {{ill|Nishinari District|de|Nishinari-gun|ja|西成郡|zh|西成郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishinari District|qq=}}, {{ill|Settsu Province|de|Provinz Settsu|ja|摂津国|zh|摄津国|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Settsu Province|qq=}} in the 13th year of {{ill|Kyōhō|de|Kyōhō|ja|享保|zh|享保|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kyōhō|qq=}} ([[1729]]). The area where the shrine stands was originally a large pond called {{ill|Fukono Pond|de|Fukono-Teich|ja|深野池|zh|深野池|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukono Pond|qq=}}, which was reclaimed as "{{ill|Fukono Shinden|de|Fukono-Shinden|ja|深野新田|zh|深野新田|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukono Shinden|qq=}}" through renovations of the {{ill|Yamato River|de|Yamato-Fluss|ja|大和川|zh|大和川|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato River|qq=}} during the Edo period. Consequently, {{ill|Hiranoya Mataemon|de|Hiranoya Mataemon|ja|平野屋又右衛門|zh|平野屋又右卫门|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiranoya Mataemon|qq=}}, an Osaka {{ill|wealthy merchant|de|wohlhabender Kaufmann|ja|豪商|zh|富商|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wealthy merchant|qq=}}, who was granted reclamation rights by the {{ill|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|de|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|ja|真宗大谷派難波別院|zh|真宗大谷派难波别院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|qq=}}, invited the spirit from {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|lt=Ikasuri Shrine|lt=Zama Shrine|de|Zama-Schrein|ja|坐摩神社|zh|坐摩神社|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zama Shrine|qq=}} (currently in {{ill|Chūō-ku, Osaka|de|Chūō-ku (Osaka)|ja|中央区 (大阪市)|zh|中央区 (大阪市)|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chūō-ku, Osaka|qq=}}) as a guardian deity, marking the origin of this shrine.

{{ill|Zama-no-Kami|de|Zama-no-Kami|ja|座摩神|1=Ikasuri no Kami|2=ja|3=座摩神|4=zh|5=坐摩巫祭神|zh|座摩神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zama-no-Kami|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikasuri no Kami|qq=}} generally refers to five deities: Ikui, Sakui, Tsunagai, Hahiki, and Asuha. However, shrine records from the {{ill|Taishō period|de|Taishō-Zeit|ja|大正|zh|大正时代|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Taishō period|qq=}} specifically mention Asuha Ōkami and Hahiki Ōkami as the two enshrined deities. Zama-no-Kami is revered as the protector of the {{ill|Imperial Palace|de|Kaiserpalast|ja|皇居|zh|皇居|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Imperial Palace|qq=}} and worshipped for household protection, safe travel, and childbirth.

West of Zama Shrine once stood the {{ill|Hiranoya Meeting Hall|de|Hiranoya-Treffpunkt|ja|平野屋会所|zh|平野屋会所|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiranoya Meeting Hall|qq=}}, which was demolished in 2008.<ref>[https://trystero.exblog.jp/7094448/ 大東市、平野屋新田会所が解体の危機 ]</ref>

