It is related to [[Ikasuri Shrine]]

== History ==
The exact date and origin of its founding are unknown. According to shrine traditions, Zama Shrine (Zama Daijingū) was the [[:en:Sōja shrine|Sōja]] of {{ill|Nishinari District|de|Nishinari-gun|ja|西成郡|zh|西成郡|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishinari District|qq=|1=Nishinari district|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10968332}}, [[:en:Settsu Province|Settsu Province]] in the 13th year of [[:en:Kyōhō|Kyōhō]] ([[:en:1729|1729]]). The area where the shrine stands was originally a large pond called {{ill|Fukono Pond|de|Fukono-Teich|ja|深野池|zh|深野池|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukono Pond|qq=|1=Fukono Pond|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11560330}}, which was reclaimed as "{{ill|Fukono Shinden|de|Fukono-Shinden|ja|深野新田|zh|深野新田|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukono Shinden|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}" through renovations of the [[:en:Yamato River|Yamato River]] during the Edo period. Consequently, {{ill|Hiranoya Mataemon|de|Hiranoya Mataemon|ja|平野屋又右衛門|zh|平野屋又右卫门|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiranoya Mataemon|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, an Osaka {{ill|wealthy merchant|de|wohlhabender Kaufmann|ja|豪商|zh|富商|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wealthy merchant|qq=|1=gōshō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11634379}}, who was granted reclamation rights by the {{ill|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|de|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|ja|真宗大谷派難波別院|zh|真宗大谷派难波别院|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|qq=|1=Namba Betsuin|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11583062}}, invited the spirit from [[:en:Ikasuri Shrine|Zama Shrine]] (currently in [[:en:Chūō-ku, Osaka|Chūō-ku, Osaka]]) as a guardian deity, marking the origin of this shrine.

{{ill|Zama-no-Kami|de|Zama-no-Kami|ja|座摩神|1=Ikasuri no Kami|2=ja|3=座摩神|4=zh|5=坐摩巫祭神|zh|座摩神|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zama-no-Kami|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikasuri no Kami|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} generally refers to five deities: Ikui, Sakui, Tsunagai, Hahiki, and Asuha. However, shrine records from the [[:en:Taishō era|Taishō period]] specifically mention Asuha Ōkami and Hahiki Ōkami as the two enshrined deities. Zama-no-Kami is revered as the protector of the [[:en:Tokyo Imperial Palace|Imperial Palace]] and worshipped for household protection, safe travel, and childbirth.

West of Zama Shrine once stood the {{ill|Hiranoya Meeting Hall|de|Hiranoya-Treffpunkt|ja|平野屋会所|zh|平野屋会所|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiranoya Meeting Hall|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, which was demolished in 2008.<ref>[https://trystero.exblog.jp/7094448/ 大東市、平野屋新田会所が解体の危機 ]</ref>

