'''Zama Shrine''' (坐摩神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in Hiranoya, {{ill|Daitō, Osaka|en|Daitō, Osaka|WD=Q386668|lt=Daitō City|1=Daitō, Osaka}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|en|Osaka Prefecture|WD=Q122723|lt=Osaka Prefecture|1=Osaka Prefecture}}.

<br />
[[Zama Shrine (Daito City)|Sazama Shrine (Daito City)]] is a regional [[Sōja shrine|Sōja shrine]]. It enshrines many kami of the local region.

It contrasts with provincial Soja shrines which enshrine all the kami of a province<ref>https://archive.ph/wip/XtZfZ</ref>

It is related to [[Ikasuri Shrine]]

== History ==
The exact date and origin of its founding are unknown. According to shrine traditions, Zama Shrine (Zama Daijingū) was the {{ill|Sōja shrine|en|Sōja shrine|WD=Q1107129|lt=Sōja|1=Sōja shrine}} of {{ill|Nishinari District|de|Nishinari-gun|ja|西成郡|zh|西成郡|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nishinari District|1=Nishinari district|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10968332}}, {{ill|Settsu Province|en|Settsu Province|WD=Q864163|lt=Settsu Province|1=Settsu Province}} in the 13th year of {{ill|Kyōhō|en|Kyōhō|WD=Q1145048|lt=Kyōhō|1=Kyōhō}} ({{ill|1729|en|1729|WD=Q6952|lt=1729|1=1729}}). The area where the shrine stands was originally a large pond called {{ill|Fukono Pond|de|Fukono-Teich|ja|深野池|zh|深野池|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukono Pond|1=Q11560330|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11560330}}, which was reclaimed as "{{ill|Fukono Shinden|de|Fukono-Shinden|ja|深野新田|zh|深野新田|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fukono Shinden|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}" through renovations of the {{ill|Yamato River|en|Yamato River|WD=Q9001527|lt=Yamato River|1=Yamato River}} during the Edo period. Consequently, {{ill|Hiranoya Mataemon|de|Hiranoya Mataemon|ja|平野屋又右衛門|zh|平野屋又右卫门|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiranoya Mataemon|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, an Osaka {{ill|wealthy merchant|de|wohlhabender Kaufmann|ja|豪商|zh|富商|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/wealthy merchant|1=gōshō|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11634379}}, who was granted reclamation rights by the {{ill|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|de|Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|ja|真宗大谷派難波別院|zh|真宗大谷派难波别院|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinshū Ōtani-ha Namba Betsuin|1=Namba Betsu-in Temple|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11583062}}, invited the spirit from {{ill|Ikasuri Shrine|en|Ikasuri Shrine|WD=Q11425667|lt=Zama Shrine|1=Ikasuri Shrine}} (currently in {{ill|Chūō-ku, Osaka|en|Chūō-ku, Osaka|WD=Q876485|lt=Chūō-ku, Osaka|1=Chūō-ku, Osaka}}) as a guardian deity, marking the origin of this shrine.

{{ill|Zama-no-Kami|de|Zama-no-Kami|ja|座摩神|1=Ikasuri no Kami|2=ja|3=座摩神|4=zh|5=坐摩巫祭神|zh|座摩神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zama-no-Kami|13=User:Immanuelle/Ikasuri no Kami|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} generally refers to five deities: Ikui, Sakui, Tsunagai, Hahiki, and Asuha. However, shrine records from the {{ill|Taishō era|en|Taishō era|WD=Q329174|lt=Taishō period|1=Taishō era}} specifically mention Asuha Ōkami and Hahiki Ōkami as the two enshrined deities. Zama-no-Kami is revered as the protector of the {{ill|Tokyo Imperial Palace|en|Tokyo Imperial Palace|WD=Q500681|lt=Imperial Palace|1=Tokyo Imperial Palace}} and worshipped for household protection, safe travel, and childbirth.

West of Zama Shrine once stood the {{ill|Hiranoya Meeting Hall|de|Hiranoya-Treffpunkt|ja|平野屋会所|zh|平野屋会所|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiranoya Meeting Hall|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, which was demolished in 2008.<ref>[https://trystero.exblog.jp/7094448/ 大東市、平野屋新田会所が解体の危機 ]</ref>

